If `n_k A = 1`, then the sum formula must still hold. But if `n_k A = 1` for some `A ∈ S'`, then `q^n - 1 = q - 1 + (q^n - 1)/(q-1) + ∑_{B ≠ A} (q^n - 1)/(q^{n_k B} - 1)`. This would mean that `(q^n - 1) - (q-1) - (q^n - 1)/(q-1)` must be non-negative and equal to the sum of positive terms (since `q^n - 1 > 0` and `q^{n_k B} - 1 > 0` for `n_k B ≥ 1`).
